<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,152,448]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,152,179]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the key to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1856" box="[550,667,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[550,667,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Megaselia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males of the British Isles (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[971,1117,153,179]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref21228" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 47 where neither option fits due to their very different hypopygia. Of four omitted Palaearctic species, 3 have brown palps and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schmitz)" authorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[151,360,222,249]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tama">
<emphasis box="[151,243,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. tama</emphasis>
(Schmitz)
</taxonomicName>
has a very different hypopygium. In the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmitz, H." box="[884,1056,221,248]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="465 - 512" refId="ref22258" refString="Schmitz, H. (1958) Phoridae. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region. 4 (33). Lieferung 202. E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, pp. 465 - 512." type="book chapter" year="1958">Schmitz (1958)</bibRefCitation>
to Abteilung III it runs to couplets 17 or 26. At 17 both options have very different hypopygia. At couplet 26 again the hypopygia for both options are clearly different. Some 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmitz" authorityName="Schmitz" box="[417,690,289,315]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvicapilla">
<emphasis box="[417,590,289,315]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. curvicapilla</emphasis>
Schmitz
</taxonomicName>
may run to this couplet instead of 17, its darker venter with much more numerous and more robust hairs instantly distinguishes it. The later described 
<taxonomicName authority="Delage &amp; Lauraire (1970)" authorityName="Delage &amp; Lauraire" authorityYear="1970" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haranti">
<emphasis box="[1097,1217,322,348]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. haranti</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Delage, A. &amp; Lauraire, M. C." pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="450 - 458" refId="ref21093" refString="Delage, A. &amp; Lauraire, M. C. (1970) trois nouvelles especes de phoridae (dipteres, brachyceres, Cyclorrhaphes), trouvees a Peyresq (Alpes de Provence). Bulletin des Recherches Agronomiques de Gembloux, 5, 450 - 458." type="journal article" year="1970">Delage &amp; Lauraire (1970)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
will run to this couplet, its 5 axillary bristles and longer hairs below the hind femur rule it out. It fails to key out for the rest of the world.
</paragraph>
